101. Refers to the practice of rubbing steel against flint-stone, so as to produce sparks. The steel for this purpose is called in modern Syriac [Syr.] (Chakmak), not [Syr.]. The [Syr.] is a very hard yellow stone, sharp as a razor, often used to shave with; while [Syr.] (Kau) is the name for the cotton used in catching the spark. To make this [Syr.], grass is burnt to cinders, and water is poured on the cinders; the water is allowed to stand for two days, after which it becomes quite yellow; cotton is soaked in it for a few hours; it is then dried, and becomes easily ignited.\par
